INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(120, 1, '2013-06-17 23:47:14', '2013-06-18 03:47:14', 'Something we discovered while doing focus groups for Thrive was that most folks have heard the word ‘probiotics’ but few seemed to know what probiotics are or why they are important for digestive health. Of course, almost everyone understands the basic idea of ANTIbiotics and has experience with them so let’s start there in our exploration of the “culture wars” – probiotic cultures vs antibiotic cultures.\r\n\r\nAntibiotics are bacteria designed to kill the harmful bacteria making you sick while minimizing damage to the “good” bacteria in your body that keep you healthy. About 90% of antibiotic substances are natural products made from other, friendlier types of bacteria and fungi (molds). 1. We have all heard that antibiotics should not be prescribed for viral infections but you may not know why. It is because viruses are not living organisms but bacteria are – and antibiotics only kill living bacteria. A virus has to inject its DNA into a living “host” cell in order to survive – it cannot survive on its own like a bacteria. A virus depends on the cell for replication because it does not have the ability to reproduce on its own. Bacteria – both good and bad – are living, self-replicating organisms. 2\r\n\r\nAlthough antibiotics are designed to minimize damage to the good bacteria in your body, there is collateral damage to your microbiome every time you take a round of antibiotics. Sometimes, we (and our children!) are prescribed antibiotics when we don’t really need them, adding to the harm done to the positive, helpful bacteria that live in our digestive systems.\r\n\r\nMany of us have heard (and heeded!) the advice to eat a lot of yogurt during and after a round of antibiotics. The reason why is that yogurt contains live bacteria cultures of the good kind – and the kind that often get killed unintentionally – by many antibiotics. These ‘good bacteria’ are known collectively as probiotics – and the good news is that Thrive has four types of the probiotics recommended to help maintain a healthy digestive system! Many people – adults and children alike – don’t really like yogurt. Until now, these folks did not have a lot of options for getting probiotics packaged in something they like to eat. Thrive solves this problem because who doesn’t like ice cream!! With four delicious flavors packed with protein, vitamins and probiotics – it is an easy and DELICIOUS way to help maintain a healthy digestive system, whether you are taking antibiotics or not!\r\n\r\nIn my next article, I will dig deeper into the four types of probiotics in Thrive and the Thrive manufacturing process that ensures these cultures are provided to you at the optimum levels. Until then, don’t forget to download your coupon for $1 off your next purchase of Thrive!', 'The Probiotic Scoop', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-probiotic-scoop', '', '', '2013-09-30 12:55:18', '2013-09-30 16:55:18', '', 0, 'http://thrive.dev.srginsight.com/?p=120', 0, 'post', '', 0);
